ln 601 a Council was held in Rome in which the privileges of the monastic orders were settled. Many rules were made for the govemment of reli- gious homes, not only at that time, but frequently during the pontificata of S. Gregory, who devoted much care to the perfectiori of the monastic life. The love which hc had been taught in his youth for the mle of S. Benedict he never ceased to cherish.

ln 602 the Emperor Mauritius was put to death with his whole family by Phocas a usurper. For the sake of the Church, Gregory secured the good- will of the new emperor. ln the following year the war between the Lombards and the empire was renewed. '

On the 12th March 604, after a life of un- wearied activity in the service of his heavenly Mas- ter‚ S. Gregory slept in the Lord, Till the last his chief care was for the Church, and particularly for his English mission. S. Hildefonsus archbishop of Toledo in the 7th century writes thus of him; “He surpassed Antony in holiness, Cyprian in eloquence, and Augustin in wisdom.” Yet so great was his humility that he subscribed himself “Servant of the servants of God,'' a style which his successors in the chair of S. Peter have retained till this day.
